{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/the-cauchy-distribution-your-distribution-so-fat-877c2cbad46d", "time": 1683018341.9229069, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/the-cauchy-distribution-your-distribution-so-fat-877c2cbad46d/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "The Cauchy Distribution \u2014 Your distribution so fat\u2026 | by Borun Chowdhury Ph.D. | Towards Data Science", "h1": "The Cauchy Distribution \u2014 Your distribution so fat\u2026", "description": "Yesterday I wrote an article on why most articles on medium about the central limit theorem are misleading because they claim that irrespective of the underlying distribution, the sample mean tends\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://borundev.medium.com/why-most-articles-on-the-central-limit-theorem-are-misleading-881bd6f830c7", "anchor_text": "why most articles on medium about the central limit theorem are misleading", "paragraph_index": 0}], "all_paragraphs": ["Yesterday I wrote an article on why most articles on medium about the central limit theorem are misleading because they claim that irrespective of the underlying distribution, the sample mean tends to Gaussian for large sample size. This is incorrect and the Cauchy distribution is a counter example. I imagine this oversight originates from several folks not being fluent with fat tailed distributions and even fewer knowledgeable of distributions like the Cauchy distribution that do not have well defined means and/or variances.", "If I were to hazard a guess, I would say that most people are not aware of this deliciously esoteric distribution because most people cannot relate to it. After all, while the uniform distribution and the normal distributions are ubiquitous, when was the last time you saw a physical process whose results are drawn from the Cauchy distribution?", "Well look no further. In this article I will explain, with some python simulation code, a thought experiment attributed to Mandelbrot. We imagine an archer who has been blindfolded and is standing 1 m from an infinite wall shooting arrows at all angles uniformly.", "Obviously, half the arrows miss but the other half hit the wall at different locations. In fact, it is easy to convince oneself that the location is given by", "So we can now write some python code to simulate the process and see the distribution of arrows on the wall", "A run of this is shown below. Each histogram has 500 points and the variation in the plots is a consequence of the fact that the distribution is so fat tailed it does not have a well defined mean and variance.", "For those of you who are mathematically inclined it is straightforward to derive the distribution. Given the relation between y and theta we can go from the probability density function of theta to that of y by", "Since the angular distribution is uniform we get", "Which is the probability density function of the Cauchy distribution. We can see why the mean and variance are ill defined. To compute mean we need to integrate y with the above measure which does not converge. For the variance we need to integrate y squared with the above measure which obviously also does not converge.", "The Cauchy distribution can be seen as arising from a process that is not at all esoteric \u2014 a simple act of drawing angles from a uniform distribution. Yet, it has no mean and variance and thus sample means are wildly fluctuating as is evident from the histograms above. This property means that sample means are not distributed normally not matter the sample size.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Formless and shapeless pure consciousness masquerading as a machine learning researcher, a theoretical physicist and a quant."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F877c2cbad46d&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------